{
  "title": "Can quantum computing crack the biggest challenges in ...",
  "url": "https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-024-03369-w",
  "content": "Quantum computing for health received a boost when funder Wellcome Leap initiated the Quantum for Bio challenge in September 2023. The non-profit organization, which was launched with $300 million from the Wellcome Trust in 2020 and aims to invest in high-risk breakthrough technologies, challenged 12 teams to identify, develop and demonstrate biology and health applications that can be run on quantum computers expected to emerge in the next 3â€“5 years. [...] Still, this year, Cleveland Clinic and IBM were able to demonstrate the potential of quantum computing in an early proof of concept. They ran a hybrid model that combines quantum and classical computing methods to model the structure of a catalytic loop of the Zika virus NS3 helicase. The result was published as part of a perspective in the Journal of Chemical Theory and Computation in May 2024 (ref. 2.\")). The authors assert that this model outperformed both a classical physics-based method [...] One strength of quantum computers is that they could soon become much better than classical computers at simulating quantum mechanics. Cracking how to use quantum computers to calculate steps that rely heavily on quantum chemistry, for instance, could unlock faster and more accurate modeling. Cleveland Clinic and IBM are looking to use quantum simulations to improve the current models of biochemical reactions. These first-of-their-kind algorithms could lead to new therapies, the researchers"
}

